<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="119" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="119">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="119">
Referring to the life inside tree wood (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="119">arbor</emphasis>
Lat. = tree + 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="119">colonus</emphasis>
= settler).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="119" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="119">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="119">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="119">Colonies</emphasis>
slow-growing, moist, white or buff colours on oatmeal agar medium, lacking aerial mycelium. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="119">Sporulation</emphasis>
conidia formed on hyphal cells. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="119">Conidiophores</emphasis>
reduced to conidiogenous cells. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="119">Conidiogenous cells</emphasis>
enteroblastic, intercalary, reduced to short discrete phialides or, more often, collarettes formed directly on hyphal cells, collarettes short tubular to funnel-shaped. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="119">Conidia</emphasis>
aggregated around the hyphae, small, hyaline, 1-celled, cylindrical, ovoidal to allantoid. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="119">Vegetative hyphae and phialides</emphasis>
hyaline, smooth-walled, septate, branched.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
